<h2><a name="inline" id="inline">inline</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="kw2">inline</span> <span class="kw4">int</span> functionA<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">int</span> a <span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#123;</span>
    ...
    <span class="br0">&#125;</span></pre>
<p>
The inline keyword requests that the compiler expand a given function in place,
as opposed to inserting a call to that function. The inline keyword is a
request, not a command, and the compiler is free to ignore it for whatever
reason.
</p>

<p>
When a function definition is included in a class definition, the compiler
should try to automatically inline that function. No inline keyword is
necessary in this case.
</p>

</div>
